'''Artifact Puzzles''' is a manufacturer of wooden [[jigsaw puzzles]] operating out of Menlo Park California in Silicon Valley.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://inmenlo.com/2014/04/14/good-news-for-jigsaw-fans-menlo-park-is-home-to-artifact-puzzles | title=Good News For Jigsaw Puzzle Fans | author=Linda Hubbard Gulkar|date=April 14, 2014 | publisher=InMenlo}}</ref> The business was founded in 2009<ref>{{cite journal | author =Tom Cutrofello |date=February 2010 | title = Pieces of Art: Cutting Edge Jigsaws | journal = Games Magazine | publisher = Kappa Publishing Group, Inc.}}</ref> by University of Washington electrical engineering professor Maya Gupta, and was originally based in [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]], [[Washington state|Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washington.edu/news/articles/elegance-engineering-combine-in-maya-gupta2019s-high-end-jigsaw-puzzles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627054116/http://www.washington.edu/news/articles/elegance-engineering-combine-in-maya-gupta2019s-high-end-jigsaw-puzzles |dead-url=yes |archive-date=June 27, 2011 |title=Elegance, engineering combine in Maya Gupta's high-end jigsaw puzzles |author=Peter Kelley |date=June 22, 2011 |publisher=UW Today }}</ref> Unlike traditional wooden jigsaw puzzles which are hand-cut by [[Jigsaw (power tool)|jigsaw]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/science/07jigsaw.html?pagewanted=all |title=Eye for Art and Artistry Amid Jigsaw's Jumble |author=Jennifer A. Kingson |date=December 6, 2010 |publisher= The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Jigsaw Puzzle, Piecing Together A History |last=Williams |first=Anne D. |year=2004 |publisher=Berkley Books |isbn=0-425-19820-0 |pages=270}}</ref> Artifact Puzzles laser-cuts 1/4" thick 3-ply [[plywood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daddoes.com/5719/review-artifact-jigsaw-puzzles/ |title=Artifact Puzzles Bring Puzzling Pieces With New Old Fashioned Jigsaw Puzzles |author=NESSEL |date=May 3, 2012}}</ref>
The puzzle pieces are designed by an artist for each new puzzle,<ref name="O'Brien">{{cite news |title=Pieces Fall Into Place |author=Chris O'Brien |url=http://news.morningstar.com/all/ViewNews.aspx?article=/ACQ/ff80808133f3b0fa013418359504787d_univ.xml |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |date=Dec 7, 2011}}</ref> and do not follow a consistent style of cut. For example, some of their puzzles have traditional knob connectors, while others have piece connectors shape like clouds, hearts, bird feet, horse hooves, and ancient Greek symbols. Like traditional wooden jigsaw puzzles, most of their puzzles have "whimsy pieces", which are pieces shaped like recognizable objects.<ref name="O'Brien"/> These pieces are designed to match the theme of each puzzle, and range from a cow jumping over a moon in one of their [[Daniel Merriam]] puzzles, to pieces shaped like ballerinas in their [[Degas]] puzzle. The company has designed and manufactures over 250 different puzzles of a broad range of art, with an unusually large selection of whimsical neo-surrealist art and 16th century art.
