{{Refimprove|date=January 2013}} [[Image:Michael Thonet 14.jpg|thumb|150px|[[No. 14 chair]] ]] [[File:Ngv, Gebrüder Thonet, culla, 1870 circa.JPG|thumb|Cradle by [[Gebrüder Thonet]] (ca. 1870)]] '''Bentwood''' objects are those made by wetting wood (either by soaking or by steaming), then bending it and letting it harden into curved shapes and patterns.
In furniture making this method is often used in the production of [[rocking chair]]s, cafe chairs, and other light furniture. The iconic [[No. 14 chair]] by [[Gebrüder Thonet|Thonet]] is a well-known design based on the technique. The process is in widespread use for making casual and informal furniture of all types, particularly seating and table forms. It is also a popular technique in the worldwide production of furniture with frames made of heavy cane, which is commonly imported into European and Western shops.
[[File:Tsimshian box (UBC-2009).jpg|thumb|A [[Thuja plicata|red cedar]] [[Tsimshian]] bentwood box dating from the 1880s, on display at the [[UBC Museum of Anthropology]]]] '''Bentwood boxes''' are a traditional item made by the [[First Nations]] people of the North American west coast including the [[Haida people|Haida]], [[Gitxsan people|Gitxsan]], [[Tlingit people|Tlingit]], [[Tsimshian people|Tsimshian]], [[Alutiiq people|Sugpiaq]], [[Aleut people|Unangax]], [[Yupik peoples|Yup'ik]], [[Inupiat people|Inupiaq]] and [[Coast Salish peoples|Coast Salish]]. These boxes are generally made out of one piece of wood that is steamed and bent to form a box. Traditional uses of the boxes was varied and included storage of food goods, clothing and for burial. They were often without decoration while others were decorated elaborately. Today many are made for collectors and can be purchased from museums, gift shops and online sites as well as directly commissioned from the artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Treasures Gallery - Bentwood storage boxes|publisher=[[Canadian Museum of Civilization]]|url=http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/tresors/treasure/237eng.shtml|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Haida Gwaii … "Islands of the People"|publisher= [[Haida Heritage Centre]]|url=http://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/eng/1100100014557/1100100014563 |date=2010-09-15|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Collection Online: Bentwood|publisher=[[Museum of Anthropology at UBC]]|url=http://collection-online.moa.ubc.ca/collection-online/search?keywords=bentwood|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Haida Art|author=George MacDonald|publisher=University of Washington Press|year=1996}}</ref>
The [[Aleut people|Aleut or Unangan People]] of Alaska made [[Unangan hunting headgear|hunting visors]], called ''chagudax'', out of driftwood using the bentwood method. The visors were used by hunters who were in kayaks. They are said to help keep the sea spray off the face as well as improve hearing. They were often decorated with paints, beads, sea lion whiskers and ivory figurines. [[Andrew Gronholdt]] is credited with reviving the art of chagudax carving in the 1980s. Present day Unangan artists create chagudax for ceremonial purposes and offer them for sale to the public as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alaska Native Collections Smithsonian Institution|url=http://alaska.si.edu/record.asp?id=18|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ancient Aleut Art of Making Bentwood Visors Showcased at Anchorage Museum |url=http://articles.ktuu.com/2012-03-09/hat_31141973 |accessdate=14 March 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130721033108/http://articles.ktuu.com/2012-03-09/hat_31141973 |archivedate=21 July 2013 |df= }}</ref>
