The '''Ninian Central Platform''' is an [[oil platform]] in the [[North Sea]]. When constructed in [[Loch Kishorn]], [[Scotland]] in 1978 the 600,000&nbsp;tonne platform was the world's largest man-made movable object<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-24613862 "Highland councillors approve Kishorn plan"], 22 October 2013, BBC</ref> before being towed to its current position and fixed to the sea floor.

It is a circular concrete gravity structure, 140&nbsp;m in diameter at its base, with seven concentric walls of stepped heights intersected by radial walls at 45-degree angles. A 14&nbsp;m wide central shaft is surrounded by a breakwater wall ("Jarlin Wall") 45&nbsp;m in diameter and 1.6&nbsp;m thick pierced with 1.5m diameter holes. Between these two walls drill slots are arranged for drilling up to 42&nbsp;wells.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://ntlsearch.bts.gov/tris/record/tris/00189457.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929124550/http://ntlsearch.bts.gov/tris/record/tris/00189457.html |archivedate=2007-09-29 |df= }} </ref>

Originally operated by Chevron Petroleum (UK), a division of [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], it is currently operated by [[Canadian Natural Resources|CNR International]].

