{{unreferenced|date=March 2009}} [[File:Bas Relief of Tribute Bearer, Persepolis, Iran (4693775791).jpg|thumb|upright|Waterskin bearer. in [[Persepolis]]]] A '''waterskin''' is a receptacle used to hold water. Normally made of a sheep or cow bladder, it retains water naturally and therefore was very useful in [[desert]] crossings until the invention of the [[canteen (bottle)|canteen]]. It is still used in some developing nations. Though it may have been used over 5000 years ago by tribal peoples, the first pictures of it are from ancient [[Assyria]]ns, who used the bladders as floats in 3000<!-- Citation needed --> B.C. It also was used by large [[Ancient history|ancient]] [[empire]]s such as [[Roman Empire|Rome]] before the advent of the [[Canteen (bottle)|canteen]].
Modern waterskins are often made of various plastic or rubber impregnated canvases, or sometimes simply thicker transparent plastics, and are often called water-pouches, water bags, or water bladders. Such modern waterskins offer many features, such as detachable straw-hoses, valves, refill openings of various widths, various closures and handles, styles of covering or cases, and removable cases or carry pouches.
